{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}} {{Use New Zealand English|date=November 2016}} {{Infobox candidate |honorific-prefix = [[PhD|Dr]] | name = Jamie Whyte | image = File:Jamie Whyte (crop).jpg |image_size = | alt = Jamie Whyte on the day of the announcement of his selection as Leader by ACT | caption = Jamie Whyte on the day of the announcement of his selection as Leader by ACT | nominee = | party_election = | party = [[ACT New Zealand]] | election_date = | runningmate = | opponent = | incumbent = |order= Leader of [[ACT New Zealand]] | deputy1= vacant | term_start = 2014 | term_end = 2014 | birth_date = <!-- {{Birth date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{Birth-date and age|df=yes|Month DD, YYYY}} --> | birth_place =Auckland, New Zealand | death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{Death-date and age|df=yes|Month DD, YYYY|Month DD, YYYY}} (death date then birth date) --> | death_place = | restingplace = | restingplacecoordinates = | birthname = | citizenship = | nationality = | spouse = | partner = <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married--> | relations = | children = 2 | parents = | residence = | alma_mater = [[University of Auckland]], [[Cambridge University]] | occupation = Philosopher, management consultant | profession = | cabinet = | committees = | portfolio = | religion = | signature = | signature_alt = | website = [http://www.act.org.nz/act-party-leader-jamie-whyte ACT Party profile] | succeeded = | predecessor = [[John Banks (New Zealand politician)|John Banks]] | leader = | successor = [[David Seymour (politician)|David Seymour]] }}
'''Jamie Whyte''' is a New Zealand politician who is a former leader of [[ACT New Zealand]], a [[free market]] political party of New Zealand, and unsuccessfully contested the [[Pakuranga (New Zealand electorate)|Pakuranga electorate]] in the [[New Zealand general election, 2014|2014 general election]].<ref>{{cite news | url= http://www.nzherald.co.nz/election-2014/news/article.cfm?c_id=1503581&objectid=11195810 | title=Act leader set to play it straight | newspaper=[[The New Zealand Herald]] | date=3 February 2014 | accessdate=3 February 2014 | author=Young, Audrey}}</ref> At the election, Whyte held the first position on the party list, but Act did not achieve enough party votes to secure any list seats.<ref name="JamieWhyte">Act. [http://www.act.org.nz/jamie-whyte "Jamie Whyte"], ''[[Act New Zealand]]'', 27 October 2005. Retrieved on 18 September 2014.</ref> Soon after the 2014 general election, he resigned from the leadership of ACT.<ref name="Whyte resigns">{{cite news | url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/politics/10576531/ACTs-Jamie-Whyte-quits-as-leader | title=ACT's Jamie Whyte quits as leader | work=Stuff | date=3 October 2014 | accessdate=3 October 2014}}</ref>
Whyte is a former philosophy lecturer, currency trader and management consultant. He has written books and newspaper columns about reasoning and politics.
== Early life and academia == Whyte was born in [[Auckland, New Zealand]]. He received his undergraduate degree from the [[University of Auckland]].<ref>{{cite news | url= http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=11195695 | title=Jamie Whyte elected Act leader | newspaper=[[The New Zealand Herald]] | date=2 February 2014 | accessdate=18 September 2014 | author=Young, Audrey}}</ref> He then moved to the UK to study for an M.Phil and Ph.D at [[St John's College, Cambridge]].{{cn|date=June 2017}}
Upon graduation, Whyte remained at Cambridge University for three years as a research fellow at [[Corpus Christi College, Cambridge|Corpus Christi College]] and temporarily lectured in the Philosophy faculty. He won the ''Analysis'' journal prize for the best article by a philosopher under the age of 30.<ref>{{Cite journal|url = https://philosophynow.org/issues/101/News_March_April_2014|title = Philosopher becomes party leader|last = Roberts|first = Sue|date = March 2014|journal = Philosophy Now|accessdate = 18 September 2014|doi = |pmid = }}</ref>
==Early career== Whyte then took up a job with the New York-based management consultancy firm [[Oliver Wyman]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.lse.ac.uk/publicEvents/events/2011/20110726t1830vOT.aspx|title=Keynes v Hayek |date= 8 August 2011| publisher=London School of Economics}} </ref> He also worked as a foreign currency trader.{{cn|date=June 2017}}
==Writing and media== Since 2004, Whyte has written books for general audiences and newspaper columns, aiming to expose shoddy reasoning, especially by politicians. In 2006 he won the [[Reason Foundation]] Bastiat Prize for journalism (jointly with Tim Harford of the ''[[Financial Times]]'') and in 2010 he was named runner up.<ref>Previous Bastiat Prize Winners from [http://reason.org/news/show/1012830.html Reason Foundation], accessed June 2014.</ref> In June 2014, Whyte won the [[Institute of Economic Affairs]] Arthur Seldon Memorial Award for Excellence for ''Quack Policy''.<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.iea.org.uk/in-the-media/press-release/political-party-leader-wins-prestigious-seldon-award|title = Political party leader wins prestigious Seldon Award|last = |first = |date = 27 June 2014|work = |accessdate = 18 Sep 2014|publisher = IEA}}</ref>
He is the author of ''Crimes Against Logic'' (titled ''Bad Thoughts: A Guide to Clear Thinking'' in the UK; 2004), ''A Load of Blair'' (2005), ''Free Thoughts'' (2012) and ''Quack Policy'' (2013) and has also written columns for many notable publications, including ''[[The Times]]'', [[City A.M.|City A.M]]., [[Standpoint (magazine)|Standpoint]], ''Financial Times'' and ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]''.{{cn|date=June 2017}}
Whyte has also occasionally broadcast on [[BBC Radio 4]] and television.{{cn|date=June 2017}}
== Political career == In his youth, Whyte was a campaign volunteer for [[Bob Jones (New Zealand)|Bob Jones]]' [[New Zealand Party]] in the [[New Zealand general election, 1984|1984 general election]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=11283858|title=Leaders' first trip to ballot box|author=Cherie Howie|publisher=New Zealand Herald|date=2014-06-29}}</ref>
Despite no prior experience in political office, at a board meeting in February 2014, Whyte was elected to the ACT party's leadership, beating former MP, [[John Boscawen]]. At the same meeting, [[David Seymour (politician)|David Seymour]] was chosen as ACT's candidate for the [[Epsom (New Zealand electorate)|Epsom electorate]]<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.3news.co.nz/ACT-choices-huge-risk-for-party/tabid/1607/articleID/330702/Default.aspx|title=ACT choices huge risk for party|author=Sabin |date= 2 February 2014| publisher=3 News|first = Brook}}</ref> and Kenneth Wang was later elected as Whyte's deputy leader in April 2014.<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/politics/9944101/Kenneth-Wang-elected-Act-deputy-leader|title = Kenneth Wang elected Act deputy leader|last = Dastgheib|first = Shabnam|date = 15 April 2014|work = |accessdate = 18 Sep 2014|publisher = Stuff.co.nz}}</ref>
In the 2014 general election, ACT only won enough votes to be represented by David Seymour in the [[Epsom (New Zealand electorate)|Epsom electorate]]. After the election, on 3 October 2014 Whyte resigned from the leadership of the party, saying: "Clearly, I make this announcement with regret, however the election result is clear, and I must now turn to my career and my family." He was replaced as ACT leader by David Seymour on the day of his resignation.<ref name="Whyte resigns"/>
In February 2017, Whyte joined the [[Institute of Economic Affairs]] as Director of Research.<ref>{{cite web|title=IEA appoints new Director of Research & a new Chief Economist|url=https://iea.org.uk/media/institute-of-economic-affairs-unveils-major-new-appointments/|accessdate=20 February 2017}}</ref>
Whyte's political philosophy is [[classical liberalism]], in the tradition of [[Friedrich Hayek]].<ref>Hayek vs Keynes at the LSE (Cobden Centre), accessed June 2014.</ref>
