{{Infobox religious biography | background = #FFD068 | name = Jiaoran | native_name = 皎然 | native_name_lang = zh | image = | image_size = | caption = | religion = [[Chinese Buddhism]] | school = [[Chan Buddhism]] |lineage = | temple = Miaoxi Temple | other_names = Qingzhou | dharma_names = Jiaoran | pen_name = | nationality = Chinese | birth_name = | birth_date = 730 | birth_place = [[Wuxing District]], [[Huzhou]], [[Zhejiang]], China | death_date = {{death year and age|799|730}} | death_place = Unknown | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|latitude|longitude|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} --> | parents = | works = ''Shishi'' }} '''Jiaoran''' ({{zh|s=皎然|t=|p=Jiǎorán|w='''Chiao-jan'''}}; 730–799), also known by his courtesy name '''Qingzhou''' ({{zh|s=清昼|p=|links=no}}), was a [[Tang dynasty]] [[Chinese people|Chinese]] poet and Buddhist monk.<ref name="cat">{{cite news|author= |url=http://culture.gxnews.com.cn/staticpages/20170630/newgx5955ce1a-16316550.shtml |script-title=zh:陆羽《茶经》对中国茶史文献的贡献 |newspaper=gxnews.com.cn |date=2017-06-30 |language=zh}}</ref> Jiaoran has written more than 470 poems and was one of the three major Tang dynasty poet-monks ({{zh|s=诗僧|p=|labels=no}}), along with [[Guanxiu]] (832-912) and [[Qiji (monk)|Qiji]] (863-937). He was the 12th generation grandson of [[Xie An]] (320-385), a [[Jin dynasty (265–420)]] statesman who, despite his lack of military ability, led Jin through a major crisis—attacks by [[Former Qin]] (351-394).<ref name="poet" >{{cite news|author= Xin Shangye ({{lang|zh-Hans|辛上邪}})|url=http://bjwb.bjd.com.cn/html/2017-07/14/content_148957.htm |script-title=zh:诗僧皎然：独隐于禅 |newspaper=bjd.com.cn |date=2017-07-14 |language=zh}}</ref> His friend, [[Lu Yu]], is venerated as the Sage of Tea for his contribution to [[Chinese tea culture]] and the writer of ''[[The Classic of Tea]]''.<ref name="cat"/>
==Biography== Jiaoran was born in 730 in [[Wuxing District]] of [[Huzhou]] city, [[Zhejiang]] province. During the [[An Lushan Rebellion]] (755-763), he dwelt in seclusion and studied [[Taoism]]. When he was about forty, the Yuan-Chao Rebellion broken broke out. He received ordination as a monk in Tianzhou Temple ({{zh|s=天竺寺|p=|labels=no}}) in [[Hangzhou]], in 767, the 2nd year of the Dali period (766-779) of the Tang dynasty (618-907). He studied [[Risshū (Buddhism)|Risshū school]] at first and then converted to [[Chan Buddhism]]. He was the abbot of Miaoxi Temple ({{zh|s=妙喜寺|p=|labels=no}}).<ref name="poet" />
==Works== * ''Shishi'' ({{zh|s=《诗式》|p=|labels=no}})
