'''Paul J. Olscamp''' (August 29, 1937 – October 14, 2014) was a Canadian-American academic and university administrator, born in [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]]. While attending the [[University of Western Ontario]], Olscamp was a member of the [[Delta Upsilon]] fraternity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://duwestern.org/notable-alumni|title=Delta Upsilon at the University of Western Ontario|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100926104041/http://duwestern.org/notable-alumni|archivedate=2010-09-26|df=}}</ref> He received his [[Bachelor of Arts]] and Master of Arts degrees in 1958 and 1960, respectively. He received his [[doctorate]] in [[philosophy]] from the [[University of Rochester]] in 1962, the first such degree awarded there. His continuing love of the subject was evident during his time at [[Bowling Green State University]] (BGSU) because he taught a philosophy course almost every semester, despite managing all his duties as president.
He served as Dean of Faculties at Roosevelt University, Chicago, Illinois, from 1970 to 1972. He also taught one course each semester, including seminars on the philosophy of George Berkeley.
Olscamp served as president of [[Western Washington University]] for seven years, from 1975 to 1982.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://westerntoday.wwu.edu/news/in-memoriam-paul-olscamp|title=In memoriam: Paul Olscamp}}</ref> While president of BGSU, he held a position on the [[board of directors]] of the [[American Association of State Colleges and Universities]]. He was appointed to the National Council on the Humanities by President [[Ronald Reagan]] in 1987. In 1989 he was elected as the [[Mid-American Conference]] representative to the National Collegiate Athletic Association’s Presidents' Commission. Following his retirement from BGSU in 1995, Dr. Olscamp served as interim president of the [[University of South Dakota]] and then went on to hold the same position at [[Mayville State University]] in [[North Dakota]]. He died at the age of 77 on October 14, 2014 in [[Coeur d'Alene, Idaho]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bgsu.edu/colleges/library/cac/uarchives/bgc/page64281.html|title=President Paul J. Olscamp|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100613070501/http://www.bgsu.edu/colleges/library/cac/uarchives/bgc/page64281.html|archivedate=2010-06-13|df=}}</ref>
